# README FOR MY THESIS REPOSITORY
# NOTE: THIS IS NOT THE FINAL README! IT IS BEING UPDATED AS I'M WORKING ON IT

This repository contains the code and the pipeline for my bachelor thesis on intrusion detection under domain shift, with a focus on understanding why machine learning models fail to generalize across heterogeneous network environments.

My thesis investigates how models trained on network traffic from IoT environments behave under scenario shift and cross-domain transfer, and whether this failure can be explained through feature instability rather than model capacity alone. I will also explore transfer learning based on this, early intrusion detection as well as hybrid architectures and models and deep learning!

## Thesis focus

The core research question is not simply which model performs best, but rather:

- how domain shift affects intrusion detection performance,
- which features remain stable across scenarios,
- which features transfer across domains,
- and why strong models fail on unseen environments.

The main datasets used are:

- **IoT-23** for scenario-based intrusion detection experiments. Link for download: https://www.stratosphereips.org/datasets-iot23
- **UNSW-NB15** for cross-domain evaluation. Link for download: https://unsw-my.sharepoint.com/personal/z5025758_ad_unsw_edu_au/_layouts/15/onedrive.aspx?id=%2Fpersonal%2Fz5025758%5Fad%5Funsw%5Fedu%5Fau%2FDocuments%2FUNSW%2DNB15%20dataset&ga=1

## Current research direction

So far, the project includes:

- preprocessing and parsing of IoT-23 `conn.log.labeled` files,
- leakage-safe scenario-level splitting,
- baseline Random Forest and XGBoost models,
- Leave-One-Scenario-Out (LOSO) evaluation on both models,
- feature stability analysis across LOSO folds,
- transferability-oriented feature analysis,
- cross-dataset evaluation tooling.

A central finding of my work is that generalization failure under domain shift appears to be driven more by **instability in feature reliance** than by insufficient model complexity.

